{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17620843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17620843"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:43+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T15:46:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16650"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"16650","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/16650"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.02,0.04,0,0.89,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9341"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66127"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9341","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9341"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16650"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51584"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4926"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"5051"},{"type":"tags","id":"10069"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"22121"},{"type":"contributions","id":"22124"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66127","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/66127"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EStatins are first-line medications for treating hypercholesterolaemia and preventing cardiovascular disease.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the primary mechanism of action of statins?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Activation of cholesterol esterase","Stimulation of cholesterol excretion","Inhibition of bile acid synthesis","Competitive inhibition of HMG-CoA reductase","Inhibition of cholesterol absorption in intestine"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EStatins work through \u003Cstrong\u003Ecompetitive inhibition of HMG-CoA reductase\u003C/strong\u003E, the rate-limiting enzyme in the mevalonate pathway of cholesterol synthesis. This reduces intracellular cholesterol synthesis, leading to upregulation of LDL receptors and increased clearance of LDL cholesterol from the blood.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of cholesterol absorption in intestine\u003C/strong\u003E describes the mechanism of ezetimibe. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EActivation of cholesterol esterase\u003C/strong\u003E would increase rather than decrease cholesterol levels. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EInhibition of bile acid synthesis\u003C/strong\u003E is the mechanism of bile acid sequestrants, not statins. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EStimulation of cholesterol excretion\u003C/strong\u003E is also incorrect; while statins may indirectly increase cholesterol clearance through LDL receptor upregulation, this is not their primary mechanism. \u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBy inhibiting HMG-CoA reductase, statins not only reduce cholesterol synthesis but also affect other products of the mevalonate pathway, including ubiquinone and isoprenoids. This explains some of their pleiotropic effects and potential side effects.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Statins reduce cholesterol synthesis by competitively inhibiting HMG-CoA reductase, the rate-limiting enzyme in the mevalonate pathway.","Inhibition of HMG-CoA reductase leads to increased expression of LDL receptors on hepatocytes, enhancing LDL cholesterol clearance from blood.","The mevalonate pathway produces not only cholesterol but also other important molecules like ubiquinone and isoprenoids."],"references":["Ritter J, Flower RJ (Rod J), Henderson G (Graeme), et al.\u00a0Rang and Dale\u2019s Pharmacology. Tenth edition. Elsevier; 2024.","Australian Medicines Handbook\u00a0(online). Adelaide: Australian Medicines Handbook Pty Ltd. Available from:\u00a0https://amhonline.amh.net.au/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51584"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"16650"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51584","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51584"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-29T12:03:25+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-12-04T09:21:12+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9341"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66127"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/74"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Level I","synonyms":null,"description":"Remember (identifying and retrieving information)","position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"7"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"4926","links":{"